      <title>Canine influenza is on the rise</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANThe number of canine influenza confirmed cases in Michigan has risen to 49 since mid-July, reports WNDU.According to AVMA, dogs can get canine influenza after being exposed to the H3N8 or H3N2 virus.It is a respiratory infection which can be caused by sniffing or licking dogs who have the virus or by sharing food and water with those dogs.Sick dogs who are coughing or sneezing may also pass on the virus to healthy dogs.Dogs may also be exposed to the virus by humans whose clothings or skin have been contaminated with the it.Michigan Department of Agriculture & Rural Development mentioned in a news release, symptoms may include fever, discharge from the eyes or nose, and coughing along with lethargic behavior."However, canine influenza can also be prevented with a vaccine.James Averill, Michigan's state veterinarian, told Michigan Live, "It's important that dog owners work with their veterinarians to protect their dogs."RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Depiction of the H3N8 and the H3N2 virus.2. Depiction of how the dog may receive the virus, which then enters the lungs.3. Depiction of some of the symptoms the dog may have such as discharge from the eyes and nose.4. Depiction of the dog receiving a vaccine to prevent canine influenza.VOICEOVER (in English): "According to AVMA, Dogs can get canine influenza after being exposed to the H3N8 or H3N2 virus.""It is a respiratory infection which can be caused by sniffing or licking dogs who have the virus or by sharing food and water with those dogs.""Michigan Department of Agriculture & Rural Development mentioned in a news release, symptoms may include fever, discharge from the eyes or nose, and coughing along with lethargic behavior.""However, canine influenza can also be prevented with a vaccine."SOURCES: Michigan Live, WNDU,  Michigan Department of Agriculture & Rural Development(MDARD), American Veterinary Medical Association(AVMA)https://www.mlive.com/news/index.ssf/2018/08/canine_influenza_cases_spike_a.htmlhttp://www.wndu.com/content/news/How-to-tell-if-your-dog-has-dog-flu-490019961.htmlhttps://www.michigan.gov/mdard/0,4610,7-125-48096---,00.htmlhttps://www.avma.org/KB/Resources/FAQs/Pages/Control-of-Canine-Influenza-in-Dogs.aspx***]]></description>
