      <title>Eating certain vegetables can help prevent colon cancer</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANNew research from the Francis Crick Institute and Imperial College London is offering concrete evidence that eating certain veggies can not only keep the bowels healthy  it also protects from cancer.According to the study published in the journal Immunity, aryl hydrocarbon receptor or AhR is a protein that acts as an environmental sensor, protecting the gut from inflammatory responses to the bacteria that live in it.Scientists studied mice that couldn't produce AhR, finding that they developed gut inflammation, which progressed to colon cancer.The key to stimulating AhR is I3C or indole-3-carbinol, which is produced when vegetables from the Brassica genus like cabbage, broccoli, or kale, is digested.Mice that were fed a diet rich in I3C didn't develop inflammation or cancer. Those with cancer that were switched to the diet also ended up with fewer, more benign tumors.The team now wants to see if the veggies have the same effect on people. They're hoping to do further experiments in organoids made from biopsies of the human gut, and eventually go on to human trials.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Depiction of AhR protecting the gut from inflammation2. Depiction of mice with no AhR developing colon cancer3. Depiction of indole-3-carbinol found in vegetables of the Brassica genus4. Depiction of I3C rich diet reducing inflammation, cancerVOICEOVER (in English): "Aryl hydrocarbon receptor or AhR is a protein that acts as an environmental sensor, protecting the gut from inflammatory responses to the bacteria that live in it.""Scientists at the Francis Crick Institute and Imperial College London studied mice that couldn't produce AhR, finding that they developed gut inflammation, which progressed to colon cancer.""The key to stimulating AhR is I3C or indole-3-carbinol, which is produced when vegetables from the Brassica genus like cabbage, broccoli, or kale, is digested."Mice that were fed a diet rich in I3C didn't develop inflammation or cancer. Those with cancer that were switched to the diet also ended up with fewer, more benign tumors.SOURCES: Imperial College London, BBChttps://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/187692/broccoli-cabbage-kale-protect-against-colon/https://www.bbc.com/news/health-45171651***]]></description>
