      <title>Heat shield installed on the Orion Spacecraft</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANAccording to reports from NASA, an uncrewed Orion spacecraft will be launched during the Exploration Mission-1, beginning a three week trip to space.NASA's Orion spacecraft is 16.5 feet in diameter, one of the largest of its kind.The base structure of the heat shield has titanium truss covered with layers of carbon fiber material known as composite substrate.Large blocks of Avcoat, an ablative material, were then bonded onto the shield's surface.Avcoat has been used in the past in Apollo's heat shields and the Orion Exploration Flight Test-1. However, this time blocks were used instead of the usual injecting method.The Orion spacecraft would be taken 40,000 miles beyond the moon and back to Earth.As the spacecraft re enters Earth's atmosphere, it would need to withstand temperatures of upto 5,000 degrees Fahrenheit. This is when the ablative material will wear away, and prevent heat from being transferred to the rest of the spacecraft.The NASA engineers plan to monitor how the Orion performs in outer space and if it works well, it may soon carry astronauts into space destinations such as the Moon and Mars.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. The heatshield of the Orion Spacecraft is shown, as well as its base.2. Avcoat blocks being added onto the heatshield of the Orion Spacecraft.3. The Orion Spacecraft is seen travelling in space with the heat shield.4. The Spacecraft is seen entering Earth's atmosphere.VOICEOVER (in English): "NASA's Orion spacecraft is 16.5 feet in diameter, one of the largest of its kind.The base structure of the heat shield has titanium truss covered with layers of carbon fiber material known as composite substrate.""Large blocks of Avcoat, an ablative material, were then bonded onto the shield's surface.""The Orion spacecraft would be taken 40,000 miles beyond the moon and back to Earth.""As the spacecraft re enters Earth's atmosphere, it would need to withstand temperatures of up to 5,000 degrees Fahrenheit. This is when the ablative material will wear away, and prevent heat from being transferred to the rest of the spacecraft."SOURCES: Space Coast Daily, NASA, Phys.orghttp://spacecoastdaily.com/2018/08/heat-shield-install-at-kennedy-space-center-brings-orion-spacecraft-closer-to-space/https://www.nasa.gov/feature/heat-shield-install-brings-orion-spacecraft-closer-to-spacehttps://phys.org/news/2013-12-shield-nasa-orion-spacecraft-kennedy.html***]]></description>
