      <title>U.S. Navy re-launches 2nd Fleet in response to Russian military expansion</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANThe U.S. Navy has officially reactivated the Cold War-era Second Fleet in response to increased Russian military expansion. The fleet was originally set up in the beginning of the Cold War, with the main objective of supporting NATO against the Soviet Union. According to Politico, the move comes amid a recent surge in Russian submarine activity in the Atlantic.According to CNN, NATO and U.S. officials have said that Russian naval activity is at its highest since the end of the Cold War. The 2nd Fleet located in Norfolk, Virginia, which was deactivated in 2011, will be assigned ships, aircraft and Marine landing forces that can be deployed along the East Coast and in the North Atlantic. Vice Adm. Andrew "Woody" Lewis, who took command of the new headquarters last Friday, said he and his staff will "aggressively and quickly rebuild this command into an operational warfighting organization. According to CNN, officials say the Atlantic fleet will work with naval units like Naval Forces Europe and the Fourth and Sixth Fleets while focusing on joint, integrated training and operations in "high-end of naval warfare." The fleet will once again support NATO and the NATO Joint Force Command for the Atlantic which will be located in Norfolk as well. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Location of 2nd Fleet headquarters in Virginia2. Russian submarine traveling underwater3. 2nd Fleet will be assigned ships, aircraft and Marine landing forces4. 2nd Fleet will work with Naval Forces Europe, 4th Fleet and 6th FleetVOICEOVER (in English): "The U.S. Navy has officially reactivated the Cold War-era Second Fleet in Norfolk, Virginia in response to increased Russian military expansion." "According to Politico, the move comes amid a recent surge in Russian submarine activity in the Atlantic, as well as overall Russian military expansion." "The 2nd Fleet located in Norfolk, Virginia, which was deactivated in 2011, will be assigned ships, aircraft and Marine landing forces that can be deployed along the East Coast and in the North Atlantic." "According to CNN, officials say the Atlantic fleet will work with naval units like Naval Forces Europe and the Fourth and Sixth Fleets while focusing on joint, integrated training and operations in "high-end of naval warfare."" SOURCES: Politico, CNNhttps://www.politico.com/story/2018/08/24/navy-atlantic-fleet-russia-751660https://edition.cnn.com/2018/08/24/politics/us-navy-fleet-russia/index.html***]]></description>
